Three formats, one choice.

### `.md` for plain Markdown

Use when the content is ordinary Markdown with no Beanstalk syntax needed.

### `.bd` for Beanstalk-aware Markdown

Use when the content needs compile-time constants, nested templates or builder helpers.

### `.bst` for full Beanstalk

Use when runtime values, control flow, imports or page fragments are needed.

### Remember

- `.md` is portable. `.bd` is Beanstalk-aware. `.bst` is full power.
- Start with `.md` or `.bd` for content. Reach for `.bst` when content becomes logic.